<p><a name="Reading_and_transcribing_numbers" id="Reading_and_transcribing_numbers"></a></p>
<h3><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Chinese_numerals&amp;action=edit&amp;section=9" title="Edit section: Reading and transcribing numbers">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Reading and transcribing numbers</span></h3>
<p><a name="Whole_numbers" id="Whole_numbers"></a></p>
<h4><span class="editsection">[<a href="/w/index.php?title=Chinese_numerals&amp;action=edit&amp;section=10" title="Edit section: Whole numbers">edit</a>]</span> <span class="mw-headline">Whole numbers</span></h4>
<p>Multiple-digit numbers are constructed using a multiplicative principle; first the digit itself (from 1 to 9), then the place (such as 10 or 100); then the next digit.</p>
<p>In Mandarin, the multiplier <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%B8%A4" class="extiw" title="wikt:两">两</a> (liǎng) is used rather than <a href="http://en.wiktionary.org/wiki/%E4%BA%8C" class="extiw" title="wikt:二">二</a> (èr) for all numbers greater than 200 with the "2" numeral. Use of both 两 (liǎng) or 二 (èr) are acceptable for the number 200.(NOTE, 二 is not appropriate in the common usage of 250, namely 二百五.) When writing in the Cantonese dialect, 二 (yi<sup>6</sup>) is used to represent the "2" numeral for all numbers. In the southern Min dialect of Chaozhou (Teochew), 两 (no<sup>6</sup>) is used to represent the "2" numeral in all numbers from 200 onwards. Thus:</p>
